ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The relatively high incidence of EBLV-2 seropositive bats in some regions
of the UK revealed by this survey contrasts with the failure to detect
infectious virus in blood and saliva samples from bats. The death of the
bat handler in Scotland in 2003 confirmed unequivocally the presence of the
virus in UK bats. This circumstance -- together with the occurrence of
apparently virus-free (seropositive) bats -- has led the authors to suggest
that some bats may survive infection and excrete virus intermittently, an
interesting proposition in relation to the supposed rabies-free status of
the UK. (It is not clear from this report, however, whether all or any of
the bats from which saliva samples were taken were found to be
seropositive). - Mod.CP]
